Brachiaria brizantha

   [536.jpg]
   Authority (Hochst. ex A. Rich) Stapf
   Family Liliopsida:Commelinidae:Cyperales:Gramineae
   Synonyms Brachiaria brizantha var. angustifolia Stent & J.M. Rattray,
   Panicum brizanthum
   Common names bread grass, signal grass, pallisade grass, Ceylon sheep
   grass, pallisade signal grass, St. Luica grass (En), brachiaria de
   Abisinia, estrella de Africa, pasto alambe, pasto senal, senal, zacate
   senal, zacate signal (Sp), brizantao, brizantha, braquiarao, capim
   braquiaria, capim Marandu, capim ocinde, Marandu (Pt), Ya
   siknaentontang (Thailand)
   Editor
   Ecocrop code 536

   Notes
   BRIEF DESCRIPTION A grass with stout erect culms and broadly lanceolate
   leaves reaching a height of 0.6-1.5 m. USES Used for pasture, hay and
   silage. Also grown as ornamnetal hedges and for erosion control.
   KILLING T Will survive frost. GROWING PERIOD Perennial grass, growing
   from spring to autumn and well into the winter, being green when other
   tropical grasses are brown and dry. It grows quickly, and 90-150 days
   from sowing, it can be ready for a first, light grazing. COMMON NAMES
   Signal grass, Palisade grass, St Lucia grass, Ceylon sheep grass,
   Upright brachiaria, Bread grass, Estrella de Africa, Pasto alambe, Ya
   siknaentontang. FURTHER INF Scientific synonym: Panicum brizanthum.
   Signal grass is native of the humid and sub-humid tropical Africa. Its
   natural habitat are grassland valleys and open woodlands. In the
   tropics it found at elevations between sea level and 3000 m. Dry matter
   yields may be between 7-20 t/ha.

   Sources
